iews of the natural world. Broad in scope, clearly written, and at the center of current scholarly debates, Working the Diaspora challenges readers to alter their conceptual frameworks about Africans by looking at them as workers who, through the course of the Atlantic slave trade and plantation labor, shaped the development of the Americas in significant ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aAfricanszAmericaxHistory. 0aAgricultural laborerszAmericaxHistory. 0aAgriculturezAmericaxHistory. 0aBlackszAmericaxHistory. 0aSlave laborzAmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAfricans.  aAmericas.  aAtlantic.  aBroad.  aDiaspora.  aWorking.  aabout.  aalter.  acenter.  achallenges.  aclearly.  aconceptual.  acourse.  acurrent.  adebates.  adevelopment.  aframeworks.  alabor.  alooking.  aplantation.  areaders.  ascholarly.  ascope.  ashaped.  asignificant.  aslave.  atheir.  athem.  athrough.  atrade.  aways.  awho.  aworkers.  awritten.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814749128.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK